{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488572"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:47:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:47:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"481"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/481"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.13,0.04,0.63,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"481"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111341"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/481"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"481"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93470"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"201"},{"type":"tags","id":"238"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1787"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1898"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1921"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9470"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9735"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23224"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45214"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45217"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111341","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111341"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of progressive shortness of breath on exertion. Sometimes this is associated with a non-productive cough and vague tightness across the chest but no sharp pain. He reports mild fatigue but no fever or night sweats. He has a history of osteoporosis with two vertebral fractures five years ago but no other significant medical history. He has suffered from mild hay fever and occasional eye irritation in the past. His only medication is weekly alendronate. He is a lifetime non-smoker and works as an accountant in an office building. He lives in an apartment in the city, has no pets, and his home shows no signs of water damage or mould. He enjoys gardening and has recently taken up golf. He reports no recent travel or sick contacts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His body mass index is 32 kg/m\u00b2. There is no peripheral lymphadenopathy. He has mild thoracic kyphosis. Respiratory examination reveals fine inspiratory crackles at both lung bases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFEV1: 2.55 L (70% predicted)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFVC: 70% predicted\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFEV1/FVC: 92% (70-80%)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDLCO: 70% (\u226580%)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EKCO: 65% (80-120%)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EArterial blood gas on room air:\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EpH: 7.42 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPaCO2: 40 mmHg (35-45)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPaO2: 85 mmHg (80-100)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Obesity hypoventilation syndrome","Kyphoscoliosis","Sarcoidosis","Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis","Hypersensitivity pneumonitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with progressive dyspnoea, dry cough, and bibasal crackles, along with restrictive pattern pulmonary function tests, suggesting interstitial lung disease. The reduced DLCO with even more reduced KCO (65% vs 70%) is characteristic of parenchymal lung disease, where both gas transfer and the transfer coefficient are impaired.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdiopathic pulmonary fibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis given the age of presentation, absence of other systemic symptoms or exposures, and characteristic findings. The pattern of reduced DLCO with proportionally more reduced KCO supports intrinsic lung parenchymal disease rather than an extrapulmonary cause of restriction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObesity hypoventilation syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with daytime hypersomnolence, morning headaches, and would show hypercapnia (elevated PaCO2) on blood gas analysis. While this patient\u0027s BMI is elevated, his normal PaCO2 makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKyphoscoliosis\u003C/strong\u003E causes a restrictive pattern through mechanical limitation of chest wall expansion. While the patient does have mild kyphosis from previous vertebral fractures, the reduced KCO argues against this being the primary cause. In pure chest wall restriction, the KCO would typically be normal or elevated as the lung parenchyma itself is unaffected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcoidosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects younger adults and presents with systemic symptoms such as fatigue, fever, and lymphadenopathy. While the patient has mild fatigue and eye symptoms that might suggest sarcoidosis, his age and the absence of significant systemic features or lymphadenopathy make it less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypersensitivity pneumonitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an inflammatory lung disease caused by repeated inhalation of environmental antigens. The absence of exposure to typical triggers (such as birds, mouldy hay, or water-damaged buildings) and the lack of systemic symptoms like fever and malaise make this diagnosis unlikely. His hobbies of gardening and golf would not typically cause hypersensitivity pneumonitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis presents with progressive dyspnoea, dry cough, and bibasal crackles on examination.","Restrictive lung disease pattern shows reduced FEV1 and FVC with normal or increased FEV1/FVC ratio.","In parenchymal lung disease, both DLCO and KCO are typically reduced, with KCO often more affected than DLCO."],"references":["Martinez-Pitre PJ, Sabbula BR, Cascella M. Restrictive Lung Disease. [Updated 2022 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560880/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93470"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"481"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93470"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-12T20:36:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-12T20:39:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"481"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111341"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonym